The paper deals with the analysis of a deterministic analogue of a random walk on a graph, which is a topic that falls under the scope of discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and graph theory (cs.GT). The paper also discusses the cover time of the deterministic random walk, which is a measure of how long it takes for the walk to visit all vertices or edges of the graph, and this is a topic that falls under the scope of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also presents techniques to derive upper bounds for the cover time, which involves the use of information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper examines the short-term behavior of the deterministic random walk, which is a topic that falls under the scope of social and information networks (cs.SI).
